{{Orphan|date=February 2013}}

In mathematics, a '''minimal K-type''' is a representation of a maximal compact subgroup ''K'' of a [[semisimple Lie group]] ''G'' that is in some sense the smallest representation of ''K'' occurring in a [[Harish-Chandra module]] of ''G''. Minimal K-types were introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Vogan|authorlink=David Vogan|year=1979}} as part of an algebraic description of the [[Langlands classification]].

